[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] Web security is the practice of protecting websites and their users from damage caused by malicious third parties, who are generally called *attackers*.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] The kind of damage done can be reputational, financial, or even physical.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] It can target data that should be kept private to users, or actions that should be only made available to particular users.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] The motivations of attackers might be financial, political, or personal.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] In this part of MDN we've written guides to help web developers understand how to protect their websites, and their users, against these attacks.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] In this page we'll introduce each of these sections and list the guides they contain.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] First though, we'll list the core security practices that web developers should follow.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] Web security can be overwhelming: there are a lot of potential threats, defenses are often complex and multilayered, and the set of threats you need to consider are highly dependent on what exactly your website is doing.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] In this section we'll summarize what we think are the most important things you can do, that will offer protection against most of the threats you will encounter.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] See also the Secure Web Application Guidelines.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] The Attacks section includes guides to common attacks on websites.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] An attack is a specific technique that an attacker can use to harm websites or their users.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] Each guide covers a specific attack (or class of related attacks), explaining how it works, the conditions under which a website becomes vulnerable, and how to defend against it.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] The Defenses section includes guides to features or practices that you can use to protect yourself against various attacks.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] In general, there's a many-to-many relationship between attack and defenses.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] That is, a single defense can protect against multiple attacks, and defending against a single attack may require multiple defenses, so as to provide defense in depth.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] Note that not all defenses are described in this section: some, such as CSP or trusted types, are described inside the technology area of which they are a part.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] Not all websites are vulnerable to all attacks: which attacks a developer needs to worry about depends on the features that the site provides and how they are implemented.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] Threat modeling is a process that web developers can follow to develop a structured representation of the potential threats that their site faces, and the corresponding defenses that they should employ.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] That is, threat modeling helps you understand which attacks you need to defend against, and how to defend against them.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] Authentication is the process of verifying that an entity — such as a user of a website — is who they claim to be.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] You'll most likely need to think about authentication if you want users to sign into your website.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] If users can log into your website, there are typically things logged-in users can do, or data they can access, that you don't want to make generally available.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] This makes user account access one of the most valuable targets for attackers.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] In this set of guides we'll look at the main techniques available for authenticating users on the web, and good practices for them.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] In this section we also outline good practices for session management, which is how a website remembers the signed-in status of a user.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] The HTTP Observatory tool enables you to scan your website to check whether it's following certain good security practices.
[src:jsonwebtoken-node/web-security] Our Practical security implementation guides provide explanations of how to implement these practices, and the threats they defend against.
